Dialogue:
GS: Hello!  
DF: Hello! How can I assist you today?  
GS: What did you have for dinner?  
DF: I had dinner at Saizeriya.  
GS: Oh, nice! I went there last week too.  
DF: What dish do you usually order?  
GS: I had a hamburger. What about you?  
DF: I recently tried the young chicken prepared diavolo style.  
GS: My friend recommended that! Is it good?  
DF: Yes, it is high in protein and tastes good.  
GS: I see, you must be working out.  
DF: Yes, I attend personal training once a week.  
GS: I used to exercise regularly as a student but not much now.  
DF: What kind of exercise did you do as a student?  
GS: I did track and field for six years.  
DF: Which events did you participate in?  
GS: I ran the 100m and 200m sprints.  
DF: That's impressive.  
GS: There were many fast runners, so I didn't stand out much.  
DF: Competitive events often have many strong participants.  
GS: Yes, it was hard to make it to the finals.  
DF: It's commendable that you continued for six years.  
GS: I started in junior high and continued until I began studying for entrance exams in high school.  
DF: Why did you choose track and field?  
GS: I performed well in a small meet in 6th grade, and my teacher recommended it.  
DF: So, you've been competing since elementary school?  
GS: I could run faster than my peers, so I was allowed to participate.  
DF: I was slower, so I'm envious of your speed.  
GS: Everyone has different strengths and weaknesses.  
DF: Thank you for the conversation.

GS: Good evening! Nice to meet you.
DF: Thank you in advance!
GS: What do you do on your days off?
DF: I often relax at home. Watching videos and such.
GS: Do you watch things like YouTube?
DF: Yes, I also play the Switch.
GS: Ah, I see. Do you play games often?
DF: Sometimes, but there are a few I bought and haven't played yet.
GS: I see. I tend to play simulation games.
DF: Are simulation games relaxed and leisurely?
GS: The game I'm playing is one where you drive a train. You can take your time if you want.
DF: I understand. I often play RPGs.
GS: There are various types of games, after all.
DF: What do you do on your days off?
GS: These days, I go to karaoke to practice singing.
DF: You enjoy singing.
GS: Yes, I use precise scoring.
DF: Understood. What genre of songs do you sing?
GS: I sing songs by Ayaka, JUJU, and Spitz.
DF: That sounds challenging.
GS: Ayaka's "Mikazuki" is one of my specialties, so I'm working hard to improve.
DF: It's great that you have a favorite song.
GS: Yes, it's fun to sing.
DF: Noted.

GS: Good evening!  
DF: Good evening! How can I help you?  
GS: When you were in elementary school, did you take any lessons or activities?  
DF: Yes, I attended piano lessons, calligraphy classes, cram school, and played softball.  
GS: I also took piano and calligraphy lessons.  
DF: Understood.  
GS: Beautiful handwriting is quite important.  
DF: Calligraphy helps with that.  
GS: You mentioned piano, how many years did you play?  
DF: From age 3 until I graduated junior high, over 10 years.  
GS: That’s impressive.  
DF: I accompanied during chorus performances.  
GS: If you can accompany, you’re skilled.  
DF: Understood.  
GS: Playing accompaniment is nice. I only play solos.  
DF: Do you still play now?  
GS: Occasionally. I play an electric piano at my parents' house when I visit.  
DF: Noted.  
GS: Busy schedules reduce playing opportunities.  
DF: Understood.  
GS: I struggle with reading sheet music.  
DF: Do you rely on ears and eyes to remember?  
GS: I play many times and memorize with my hands.  
DF: Practice improves skills.  
GS: Yes, I've improved with repeated practice.  
DF: Consistent effort is effective.  
GS: Because it's something I like.  
DF: Enjoyable activities provide motivation.  
GS: Absolutely. I have more to look forward to now.  
DF: Acknowledged. Thank you for the conversation.

GS: Good evening!  
FE: Good evening! How can I assist you today?  
GS: What did you do today?  
FE: I went to the lab for research.  
GS: Is it university research?  
FE: Yes, I am a student.  
GS: I am also a student! Are you in science?  
FE: Yes, I am in science. How about you?  
GS: I am a science major as well. Engineering?  
FE: No, general science.  
GS: I understand. I’m on summer vacation and will start classes next week.  
FE: Understood. My classes started today.  
GS: I see.  
FE: Did your summer vacation start later?  
GS: Yes, around August 6th. How about there?  
FE: Similar timing here. Your summer vacation might be longer.  
GS: Spring break is shorter.  
FE: Noted. Are there a set number of classes per lesson?  
GS: Yes, it’s set. How about you?  
FE: 16 sessions.  
GS: I see. My university's location is inconvenient. How is it there?  
FE: 15-minute walk from the nearest station.  
GS: Understood. My university is in a remote area.  
FE: How do you manage your commute?  
GS: Over an hour by train and bus.  
FE: Understood. Do you live with your parents?  
GS: No, I’m renting an apartment.  
FE: The commute time sounds long.  
GS: Yes, but I use the travel time for various activities.  
FE: Utilizing travel time is efficient.

GS: Please!  
FE: Please!  
GS: Do you have any special skills?  
FE: I can play the trombone.  
GS: Nice, I play the piano.  
FE: I stopped piano after second grade.  
GS: Was that a long time ago?  
FE: Yes, my fingers were too short.  
GS: Playing octaves must have been tough.  
FE: Yes.  
GS: What pieces did you play?  
FE: Mostly Beyer.  
GS: I played Beyer too. Now, I play J-POP.  
FE: Which J-POP songs?  
GS: "Summer" by Joe Hisaishi.  
FE: I know it.  
GS: Also "Bokunote" by Sukima Switch and "Yesterday" by Hige Dandism.  
FE: "Yesterday" is hard.  
GS: Yes, very hard. Do you know CANACANA on YouTube?  
FE: Yes.  
GS: I tried their arrangement of "Yesterday".  
FE: Challenging.  
GS: It was, I eventually gave up.  
FE: Impressive effort.  
GS: Thanks. If I had more time, I might have finished it.  
FE: What are you practicing now?  
GS: I don't have a piano at home.  
FE: Noted. Hope you can get back to it soon!

GS: Please!
FE: Please!
GS: Do you have a smartphone, iPhone or Android?
FE: iPhone.
GS: I use an iPhone too.
FE: I've used an iPhone for a long time.
GS: I switched from Android.
FE: What's different about them?
GS: iPhone is faster.
FE: Newer models are more responsive.
GS: I haven't tried older models much.
FE: I've used it since iPhone 6, it's changed.
GS: Screen sizes are different.
FE: Yes, except for SE, newer ones are bigger.
GS: Sizes standardized around iPhone 10?
FE: Yes, I use an 11, one-handed use is tough.
GS: Using one hand can lead to drops.
FE: A ring might help, but it's inconvenient.
GS: Rings seem inconvenient.
FE: I used one, but it made it harder.
GS: Best not to use it.
FE: There was a recent update for iPhone.
GS: iOS 16.
FE: It's more user-friendly now.
GS: I like the slideshow lock screen.
FE: Changing the font is nice.
GS: Changing the watch face is good.
FE: Siri's voice has changed.
GS: I noticed. It's a good update.
FE: Agreed.

GS: Good evening.
FE: Good evening.
GS: Do you listen to music often?
FE: Yes, quite often.
GS: What genre do you prefer?
FE: J-POP and classical, since I play in an orchestra.
GS: Any favorite bands?
FE: Higedan and Mr. Children.
GS: I like Mr. Children too.
FE: Have you attended their concerts?
GS: No, I hope to someday.
FE: Noted. Concerts can be a great experience.
GS: Do you have a favorite song by Mr. Children?
FE: "The Monologues We Share Together."
GS: I enjoy "HANABI."
FE: "HANABI" is quite popular. I feel emotional every time I hear it.
GS: Which drama was it from?
FE: "Code Blue."
GS: Correct, "Code Blue."
FE: Glad I remembered.
GS: No problem.
FE: Have you watched any dramas recently?
GS: I watched "Galileo" recently.
FE: Interesting. I primarily watch YouTube.
GS: Masaharu Fukuyama and Kou Shibasaki are a good pair.
FE: Is there a new movie coming out?
GS: Yes, "Silent Parade."
FE: Noted. That sounds intriguing.
GS: Consider watching it at the theater.
FE: Will do. Thanks for the suggestion.

GS: Please!
FE: Please!!
GS: What model of computer are you using?
FE: Windows.
GS: I also use Windows. Considered switching to Mac.
FE: Mac is cool. I admire it.
GS: Runs smoother than Windows, I imagine.
FE: Similar to iPhone. Smooth.
GS: Great! I like iPhones.
FE: Used a Mac. Screen was beautiful.
GS: Beautiful screen. Inconveniences?
FE: Windows is easier to modify.
GS: Harder for viruses to get in, right?
FE: Correct. I install many lab applications. Prefer Windows.
GS: Advantages noted. Pros and cons.
FE: In physics research, mostly use Windows.
GS: I'm a science major. Right choice?
FE: With iPad, syncing issues. Maybe Mac is better.
GS: iPhone sync must be the best.
FE: Best. Airdrop is great.
GS: Quality of photos/videos doesn't drop.
FE: Sending through LINE drops quality.
GS: Night view quality was poor on LINE.
FE: Night views need ORIGINAL quality.
GS: ORIGINAL quality doesn't deteriorate?
FE: Oh, really?
GS: Dropped from 12 million to 8 million.
FE: Quite a drop. Didn't know.
GS: I'm shocked.
FE: AirDrop is strong.
